<br>
Worship takes many forms, some formal, some less. I grew up in a Baptist church, which was pretty informal, but I <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> had the sense that it was reverent. Does that make any sense? <br>
<br>
Then, in the late 60's early 70's in the Jesus Movement, it got really, I mean REALLY casual. But, I was always STILL aware of being reverent. But, I know others weren't, but it didn't influence me.<br>
<br>
Maybe it's a personal perspective thing.. When we're doing our study of Israel and how God's dealt with them, I get real uncomfortable with those that just zero in on the &quot;God is Love&quot; theme. He also deals out justice. <br>
<br>
So, I <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>guess</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I'd go with it's the heart. God knows our attitude. I'd say our heart influences our actions more than the other way round.... hm.. but on the other hand... people tend to go with what they learn as children, what they grow up with being comfortable. (that is IF they grow up IN a church)<br>
<br>
AACK!!! I don't know! Now, I'm going to have to think on this a bit.. <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:fuchsia;font-family:comic sans ms;font-size:x-small;">....·´¨¨))</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:purple;font-family:comic sans ms;font-size:small;">-:¦:-</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:teal;font-family:comic sans ms;font-size:x-small;"> <br>
