I agree to a certain point.  I think you're absolutely right that the condition of our heart is the most important thing.  I do also think we need to be with other believers, not that the local church is the ONLY meeting ground, but it seems to be the best opportunity to meet with those of a like mind and kindred spirit.  If we are continually cut off from corporate worship (for those who DO have the opportunity), I wonder how we can grow and function as Paul speaks of in 1 Cor. 12--one body, many parts.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I mean, if you've a bunch of folks that don't really have their heart towards God, well, even if they are in a church like setting, it's STILL not the same as a group of true believers in a not so church like setting. Does that make sense? Did I explain it right?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
