Yes, that makes sense to me <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     It's also why I see a ministry happening through places like this-- believers lifting one another in prayer, encouraging one another, etc.  I find a lot of encouragement and fellowship <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>here</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  <br>
<br>
I guess, part of my questioning/study in Malachi leans toward my belief in the sacramental nature of worship.  For example, I don't believe we can do communion 'on our own', nor do I believe that we can 'baptize' ourselves...I believe that this is the nature of the body of Christ, that we are to be interdependent on one another.   When I see that some churches only take a cursory look/attitude into these 'events', it really bothers me.  I don't want to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>over</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->emphasize the nature of baptism, or the Last Supper, or laying on of hands, etc., but too often in my experience, they have been <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>under</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->emphasized.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think this is that &quot;personality&quot; thing. Some people are not as warm, personally, as others. It's like hugging... some people just assume that EVERYone is going to hug everyone else.. I'm not like that. I don't like hugging strangers. So for me, that's an uncomfortable situation. But for others, it's just peachy! <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
