Even though it is an unbloody act there is still the concept of a sacrifice involved and some find that - for lack of a better word - unpalatable.<br>
<br>
Personally, I think of the order of the mass and the fact that what we offer is the bread and wine which then becomes the flesh and blood.<br>
<br>
Maybe it's terminology, but I can appreciate the reservations some Christians have about this aspect of Catholicism.  At the same time, I firmly believe in the presence of the body and blood in the Eucharistic celebration.  It (to me) is not only a symbolic commemorative.  However, as to the exact nature (transubstantiation, consubstantiation or Holy mystery)... well, I can appreciate where there is some debate on the issue. <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man.<br>
