<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think if we follow RCC doctrine on this we discover that definition given stops before the conclusion of the RCC position. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>It is grace given so that the person is made worthy to receive forgiveness.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> And therein lies the crucial difference with Lutheran theology of the Sacraments. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
During our service this morning (St. George Orthodox), I noticed something that may relate to your comment; perhaps you are thinking of Orthodox doctrine rather than RCC?<br>
<br>
Even though I cannot partake of communion, I do follow along with the service book and read what the Orthodox profess with regards to the Lord's Supper:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I believe, O Lord, and I confess that Thou art truly the Christ, the Son of the living God, who didst come into the world to save sinners, of whom I am first.  And I believe that this is truly Thine own immaculate Body and that this is truly Thine own precious Blood.  Wherefore, I pray Thee, have mercy on me, and pardon my transgressions both voluntary and involuntary, of word and of deed, of knowledge and of ignorance;  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>and make me worthy to partake without condemnation of Thine immaculate mysteries unto forgiveness of sins and unto life everlasting.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Amen.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
